00:02:00,149 --> 00:02:03,130
So, why care about game capture?

44
00:02:03,930 --> 00:02:06,511
Game capture is simply video footage of the game.

45
00:02:07,071 --> 00:02:13,074
You need it for trailers, animated gifs, dev blogs, b-roll for montages and press coverage.

46
00:02:13,794 --> 00:02:16,996
But most importantly, a good way to think about it is...

47
00:02:18,169 --> 00:02:21,371
more people will see your game capture than play your game.

48
00:02:22,131 --> 00:02:25,693
We'd love to think that every trailer view turns into a sale,

49
00:02:25,814 --> 00:02:28,735
but far more people will see footage of your game

50
00:02:28,955 --> 00:02:30,136
than actually play it.

51
00:02:31,777 --> 00:02:36,100
And the game capture you release is the only time

52
00:02:36,140 --> 00:02:38,901
you ever have full control over how your game looks.

53
00:02:39,622 --> 00:02:41,323
Once it's released, you have no idea

54
00:02:41,383 --> 00:02:43,664
what kind of footage will be someone's first impression

55
00:02:43,704 --> 00:02:44,224
of your game.

56
00:02:44,905 --> 00:02:46,646
So you should want to make it look good.

57
00:02:48,005 --> 00:02:53,068
Also, if you have friends, parents, or extended family who don't play games, then game capture

58
00:02:53,088 --> 00:02:55,929
might be the only way you can show them what it is that you do.

59
00:02:57,370 --> 00:03:04,254
But the main thing to think about is successful game capture communicates effectively.

60
00:03:05,035 --> 00:03:09,357
And this seems like an obvious thing to say, but if someone watches a shot that you captured

61
00:03:09,577 --> 00:03:14,920
and they don't have any idea what's happening or what the shot is trying to say, then it's

62
00:03:14,980 --> 00:03:15,741
not good capture.

63
